===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|sise|sise, syse|regulation, control, limit|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|cise||lang=fro}}, {{term|sise||lang=fro}}, aphetism of ''[[assise]]'' "assize". Displaced native {{enm}} {{term|grete|grete, grette|size|lang=enm}} (from {{ang}} {{term|grietu|grīetu, grȳtu|size, greatness|lang=ang}}).

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{obsolete|_|except|_|dialectal}} An [[assize]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* '''1749''', Henry Fielding, ''Tom Jones'', Folio Society 1973, p. 560:
#*: I know you would have women above the law, but it is all a lye; I heard his lordship say at '''size''', that no one is above the law.
# {{obsolete}} A regulation determining the [[amount]] of money paid in [[fees]], [[taxes]] etc. {{defdate|14th-18th c.}}
# {{obsolete}} A fixed [[standard]] for the magnitude, quality, quantity etc. of goods, especially food and drink. {{defdate|15th-17th c.}}
# The [[dimensions]] or [[magnitude]] of a thing; how big something is. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: ''The '''size''' of the building seemed to have increased since I was last there.''
# {{obsolete}} A [[regulation]], piece of [[ordinance]]. {{defdate|15th c.}}
# A specific set of [[dimension]]s for a manufactured article, especially [[clothing]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#: ''I don't think we have the red one in your '''size'''.''
# {{graph theory}} A number of [[edges]] in a [[graph]]. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}

